No doubt can, therefore, be entertained as to its authenticity. Shortly after its composition, and before it had come into general circulation, a certain presbyter named John, in whose welfare the author appears to have felt considerable interest, being about to visit Rome,¹ Beda inscribed the poem to his friend; partly, as he himself tells us, in token of his good wishes and partly that the traveller might derive profit and consolation from the company of the Saint. The preface, short as itis, gives a lively and agreeable picture of the mind of its author, and has all the characteristics of a private letter.
